In Java, the `==` operator is used to compare the memory locations of two objects to check if they are the same object. However, when it comes to strings, it is usually more meaningful to compare the values of the strings, i.e., whether they contain the same characters in the same order. This is where the `.equals()` method comes in.

When you compare two strings using `==`, it checks if they are the same object in memory. This means that if you have two string literals that have the same value, they may or may not be the same object in memory, depending on how they were created. For example:
```java
String s1 = "hello";
String s2 = "hello";
System.out.println(s1 == s2); // prints "true"

String s3 = new String("hello");
String s4 = new String("hello");
System.out.println(s3 == s4); // prints "false"
```
In the first example, `s1` and `s2` are both string literals with the value "hello". Since string literals are interned in Java, they are guaranteed to be the same object in memory, so `s1 == s2` returns `true`. In the second example, `s3` and `s4` are both created using the `new` operator, which creates a new object in memory, so `s3 == s4` returns `false`.

On the other hand, when you compare two strings using `.equals()`, it checks whether the two strings have the same value, i.e., whether they contain the same characters in the same order. For example:
```java
String s1 = "hello";
String s2 = "hello";
System.out.println(s1.equals(s2)); // prints "true"

String s3 = new String("hello");
String s4 = new String("hello");
System.out.println(s3.equals(s4)); // prints "true"
```
In both examples, `s1.equals(s2)` and `s3.equals(s4)` return `true` because the strings have the same value, regardless of whether they are the same object in memory.

In summary, when comparing strings in Java, it is generally better to use the `.equals()` method instead of the `==` operator, because `.equals()` checks whether the strings have the same value, whereas `==` checks whether they are the same object in memory. However, it's worth noting that if you are comparing string literals that have the same value, you can use `==` safely, since they are guaranteed to be the same object in memory.

